{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13076"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13076"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.63,0.04,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52939"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5513"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13076"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38334"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15529"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42844"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43383"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52939"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his daughter due to increasing problems caring for him at home. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears disoriented to time and place with a flat affect. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurological examination reveals a broad-based, shuffling gait with difficulty initiating steps, maintaining balance and pivoting. His tone and power are normal throughout, and there is no tremor. His peripheral reflexes are brisk with no pathological reflexes elicited. Romberg\u0027s test is positive, and finger-nose-finger test reveals dysmetria with slowed movements. The cranial nerve examination does not reveal any localised abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the examination, the patient describes urinary urgency and discomfort with urge on abdominal palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECognitive assessment reveals deficits in recent memory and attention. Executive function appears impaired, with difficulty in problem-solving tasks. There is no evidence of hallucinations during the examination and the patient and daughter deny any prior history of hallucinations or delusions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Normal pressure hydrocephalus","Vascular dementia","Lewy body dementia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 74-year-old man with a triad of symptoms characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ENormal Pressure Hydrocephalus (NPH)\u003C/strong\u003E: gait disturbance, cognitive impairment, and urinary dysfunction. These symptoms, along with the patient\u0027s age, make NPH the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENPH is characterized by the accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the brain\u0027s ventricles, leading to enlargement and increased pressure. The gait disturbance in NPH typically presents as a broad-based, shuffling gait with difficulties initiating and maintaining steady walking, as seen in this patient. Cognitive impairment in NPH often affects executive function, attention, and memory, which is consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation. Urinary urgency and/or incontinence, another cardinal symptom of NPH, is attributed to the compression of neural structures involved in bladder control by the enlarged ventricles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects memory, language, executive function, and visuospatial skills. While it remains a possibility given the patient\u0027s cognitive decline, the absence of significant memory impairment as the primary symptom and the presence of gait disturbance and urinary symptoms make it less likely than NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E results from multiple strokes or impaired blood flow to the brain. It often presents with a stepwise decline in cognitive function following each stroke. The absence of a history of stroke or significant vascular risk factors in this case makes it less likely than NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by cognitive impairment, visual hallucinations, fluctuations in alertness, and parkinsonism. The absence of prominent visual hallucinations or fluctuations in alertness in this patient makes it less likely than NPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in young, obese females and is associated with headaches, not memory impairment or dementia. The symptoms described in this case (urinary dysfunction, gait disturbance, cognitive impairment) are not typically associated with this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the classic triad of symptoms and the patient\u0027s age, NPH should be promptly investigated. Diagnosis typically involves neuroimaging (MRI or CT) to show ventricular enlargement, and a lumbar puncture may be performed for both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes. Early diagnosis and treatment of NPH can lead to significant improvement in symptoms and quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal pressure hydrocephalus characteristically presents with progressive gait impairment, cognitive deficits, and urinary urgency and/or incontinence.","The average age of onset for normal pressure hydrocephalus is approximately 70 years, affecting men and women equally."],"references":["M Das J, Biagioni MC. Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542247/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38334"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13076"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38334"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-13T11:52:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-13T11:56:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5513"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52939"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio